               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-295-person2468">
                  GEORGE 
                  FORD
               <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2468" type="surname" value="FORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2468" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2468" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable F 50.) Mr. Kimber, who is a <rs id="t18320405-295-viclabel1723" type="occupation">butcher</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-295-victim2467 t18320405-295-viclabel1723"></join>, and lives in <placeName id="t18320405-295-crimeloc1724">Bell-yard, Temple-bar</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-295-crimeloc1724" type="placeName" value="Bell-yard, Temple-bar"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-295-crimeloc1724" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-295-off1721 t18320405-295-crimeloc1724"></join>, applied to me to watch his shop, on Saturday night, the 11th of March, and about half-past three o'clock on the Sunday morning, I saw the prisoner at the bottom of Bellyard - he crossed, and went into Apollo-court; I went and knocked at the prosecutor's door, and they let me in - I had been in about ten minutes or a quarter of an hour; the prisoner then came; he got on the ledge outside, and put his arm into the shop - in a few minutes a match broke out on fire, and he could see every thing that was in the shop; I went towards the front door, on my knees - he had then got down, and got up again with a stick and a hook at the end - he fixed the hook into a breast of mutton, and drew it towards him, but it came off, and dropped into the shop- he then took another, but that also dropped in the shop; he then took a third, and that he got out - I opened the door, and pursued him with the stick and mutton in his hand; he ran up Apollo-court - I lost sight of him for a moment, but two City watchmen came up; I went into a house into which the prisoner had gone, and met him coming down stairs - the stick and the meat he had put on the stairs.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. Q. How far up the stairs did you find the meat? A. About four stairs up the second flight, where you returned to meet me; I had not lost sight of you half a minute - I did not say I did not know you without taking you to the light; the two watchmen had lights - I had not.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-295-person2469">
                  EDWARD 
                  KIMBER
               <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2469" type="surname" value="KIMBER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2469" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-295-person2469" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a butcher. I employed the officer to watch my shop; I saw a man put his arm through into my shop, and a match burst out into a light - he got down, and got up again; I saw the stick and the book stuck in the meat - I did not see his face - I was watching in the adjoining room; I have been repeatedly robbed.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I never was on the stairs - I was out of doors when he took me.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320405-295-verdict1725" type="verdictDescription">
